I rest my case.  This irrational babbling is the signature of your average &quot;protester&quot; and liberal.  Americans, aren't you proud to have the likes of Lear Parson on your team.  You could count on him/her, couldn't you?  Note the irrational connections of both respondents.<br><br>
I do most certainly believe in the right to dissent.  I blindly, stupidly followed the leaders of my country to help in any way I could to defend that right.  Myself, 57,600+ who died and tens of thousands of others who survived did that. And if it weren't for the likes of those 57,600+ tens of thousands of other foolish americans your right to protest could be endangered.  In your beloved socialist world you would have been shot.<br><br>
For all it's faults and malious people, America is the finest country on the face of the planet.  And it needs fine brave men who are willing and able to serve the leadership and the citizens. I was taught that is good citizenship.  History and everything respectable will prove that to be correct.  And even at 50 years old, if I were needed to serve my country to defend liberal, conservative, black, white, yellow, man, woman, Baptist, Jewish, Islamic, tall, short or whatever, I would do it.<br><br>
You can heep your moral indignance at our leadership, our soldiers, industrialist and whomever else you please from your hiding place in the closet.  Your accusations and guilt are aimed at your own family.  Brothers, sisters, neighbors and associates.  What is so bad about the Viet Nam war.  That moral indignance.<br><br>
For anyone who was service age in the mid 1960's from what was a mostly rural America did not have any information about Viet Nam. We couldn't even pronounce it.  We were not nearly so gifted as you.  By the way, in the mid sixties, how did you find out all this background about the immorality of the war, the history and all the political implications to raise your intellectual perspective to the point of moral outrage?
